ng and wide-ranging component of his thought. Taking up questions central to the philosophy of mind and body and to the philosophy of psychology, the Philosophy of Subjective Spirit includes discussions of feelings and emotions, consciousness, habit and free will, and rationality—as well as madness, dreams, and the paranormal. Situating Hegel's philosophy on the topic in relation to the rest of his work, to his contemporaries, and to current philosophy of mind and psychology, this volume demonstrates its richness as a focus of study and paves the way for a new direction in Hegel scholarship.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aSpiritxHistoryy19th century. 0aSubjectivityxHistoryy19th century. 4aPhilosophy : Hegel. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy of Language. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy of Mind. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy of Psychology. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh1 aBykova, Marina F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrier, Philip T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoward, Jason J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLumsden, Simon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMagee, Glenn Alexander, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMowad, Nicholas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNuzzo, Angelica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReid, Jeffrey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStern, David S., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSurber, Jere O’Neill, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTesta, Italo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb